{"pdfpcFormat":2,"disableMarkdown":false,"pages":[{"idx":0,"label":1,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Welcome the audience. Briefly say what this is NOT: a dunk on AI.\n  - It's about finding the right place on the spectrum and not handing\n    over more control than we mean to.\n  - ~30 min, plenty of room for discussion after."},{"idx":1,"label":2,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- The conversation is almost never \"AI or no AI\" — it's \"how much AI,\n    where, for what.\"\n  - Both ends are positions on the same spectrum. We can choose where to sit\n    per task, per project, per person.\n  - Using GenAI is *always* trading some control (and often quality) for\n    productivity. There is no free lunch. The question is how big the trade\n    is and whether you noticed making it."},{"idx":2,"label":3,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Two curves on the same X-axis (manual → vibecode).\n  - Quality: starts middling (humans are flawed too!), rises with judicious\n    AI assistance, then falls off a cliff when nobody is reading the diff.\n  - Productivity: low on full manual, peaks somewhere in the middle, stays\n    high-ish on full vibecode — until the bugs ship.\n  - Sweet spot is somewhere in the middle. Where exactly depends on the\n    task, the stakes, and how good you are at reviewing what the AI wrote."},{"idx":3,"label":4,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Briefly acknowledge these are the \"macro\" risks — not directly about\n    our day job, but they're the context everything else happens in.\n  - Don't dwell. One sentence each."},{"idx":4,"label":5,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- \"Trust me bro\" security model is a real phrase from the field — the\n    privacy posture of most LLM providers is essentially that.\n  - Licensing: a model can happily emit a near-verbatim chunk of GPLv3 code\n    without knowing it. You ship it, you wear it.\n  - Prompt injection and MCP attacks are a *new class* of bug — they don't\n    fit into the OWASP top 10 yet."},{"idx":5,"label":6,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- The internet that trained these models is being polluted by their own\n    output. The next generation trains on the slop.\n  - Communities like Stack Overflow and many OSS projects depended on\n    humans asking and answering. Traffic is collapsing."},{"idx":6,"label":7,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- This one matters most to us. If juniors don't get hired, where do\n    seniors come from in ten years?\n  - \"Convincing hallucinations\" — the dangerous failure mode isn't\n    \"AI gets it wrong\", it's \"AI gets it wrong and sounds right\"."},{"idx":7,"label":8,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Deliberately re-frame: we've just listed a lot of scary things, but\n    most of them are about *how* AI is deployed, not whether it exists.\n  - Schools are a clean case study because the same tool produces opposite\n    outcomes depending on use."},{"idx":8,"label":9,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- The Bastani et al. Wharton/Penn field experiment with ~1000 Turkish\n    high-schoolers is the cleanest piece of evidence.\n  - Three groups: no AI, \"GPT solver\" (gives answers), \"GPT tutor\" (gives\n    hints).\n  - Solver group did much better *during practice*, then ~17% worse on\n    the unaided exam vs control.\n  - Tutor group: no harm, and learning was much faster than unaided.\n  - VERIFY exact numbers and SSRN ID before presenting."},{"idx":9,"label":10,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- These are *our* biases — things wired into how humans process\n    suggestions from an authoritative-sounding source.\n  - For each: name it, one-line definition, why LLMs amplify it.\n  - Hint at the talk I want to do on cognitive biases more broadly."},{"idx":10,"label":11,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Dunning–Kruger here is the dangerous one for seniors *and* juniors:\n    you confuse the model's competence with your own.\n  - Atrophy isn't a bias, but it's the cumulative effect of the previous\n    biases playing out over months."},{"idx":11,"label":12,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Flip side: the model has its *own* biases, baked in statistically.\n  - Sycophancy is the most important one for our daily work — push back\n    on a correct answer and the model often caves.\n  - Attention bias: long context degrades; first/last instructions weigh\n    disproportionately.\n  - Omission bias: the rare, novel answer is statistically underrepresented\n    in training, so the model gravitates to the common one."},{"idx":12,"label":13,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- This is the slide that should make the room uncomfortable for a\n    second. The juniors-not-hired problem isn't just an economics\n    problem — it's a *verification* problem.\n  - If you don't know what good code looks like, you can't prompt for it.\n  - If you don't understand the diff, you can't review it."},{"idx":13,"label":14,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- The vibecoding subreddit meme: \"how do you know it works?\" / \"it ran\"\n  - Bridge into: real verification means having a strategy *before* you\n    accept the diff, not vibes after."},{"idx":14,"label":15,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Frame the next few slides: not commandments, just a small set of\n    habits that have worked for me and that survive contact with reality."},{"idx":15,"label":16,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Rule 1: my favourite worked example is SQL. Sketch the query yourself,\n    *then* ask the model to review and optimise. You stay in the loop;\n    the model adds value without anchoring you.\n  - Rule 2: deliberately keep some work manual. Not for purity — for skill\n    maintenance, and because the parts you do manually are the parts you\n    actually understand later."},{"idx":16,"label":17,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- This is where most teams quietly skip a step.\n  - The \"noise for Dart\" example from our work: when you can't read\n    everything the model writes, lean on automated signals — fuzz inputs,\n    property tests, regressions, smoke tests on real data.\n  - The point isn't \"more tests\". The point is: *before* you accept a\n    large generated change, name the signal that would tell you it's wrong."},{"idx":17,"label":18,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Rule 4 sounds cynical but it's just practical. The replaceable parts\n    of your job are the ones where you're acting as a slow autocomplete.\n    Stop doing those parts that way.\n  - Rule 5: collaborator, not oracle. You'd push back on a coworker. Push\n    back on the model. You'd ignore a coworker who hallucinated. Same\n    rule."},{"idx":18,"label":19,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- Peter Naur, 1985, \"Programming as Theory Building\". One of the most\n    important short papers in the field.\n  - Punchline: the code is the *artefact*. The thing that's actually\n    being built is the team's shared mental model of the problem.\n  - This is why handovers fail. Documentation captures the artefact,\n    not the theory."},{"idx":19,"label":20,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- The implication for AI is direct and uncomfortable: Claude has no\n    theory. It has a snapshot of the artefact, and whatever context\n    you put in front of it.\n  - \"Write tests for this file\" → it freezes the current behaviour\n    into tests, including the bugs. Because it has no theory of what\n    the code *should* do.\n  - Your job hasn't been automated. Your job is the theory.\n  - A design doc / decision log is more useful than CLAUDE.md, because\n    CLAUDE.md is size-limited. CLAUDE.md gets the headline; the design\n    doc gets the reasoning."},{"idx":20,"label":21,"overlay":0,"forcedOverlay":false,"hidden":false,"note":"- One sentence summary. Then open it up.\n  - If the room is quiet: start with \"where on the spectrum do you sit\n    today, and where would you like to be in six months?\""}]}